The concentrations of cAMP $c(\vec{r},t)$, PDE $p(\vec{r},t)$, cAMP-PDE complex
$C_{cp}(\vec{r},t)$ and the 5'AMP $c'(\vec{r},t)$, are obtained in the standard quasi-steady
state assumption \cite{QSSA}. This assumes that intermediate complex concentration does not change on the time scale of product formation, i.e. $k_{1}cp=(k_{-1}+k_{2})C_{cp}$, so the two relevant steady-state equations are:
\begin{equation}
		D_c\nabla^{2}c-\frac{k_2}{K_M}pc = 0, \quad
		D_p\nabla^{2}p = 0
  \label{eq:main_sys}
\end{equation}
where $D_c$ and $D_p$ are the diffusion constants of cAMP and PDE and $K_M \equiv (k_{-1}+k_2)/k_1$. 
These equations are solved numerically using COMSOL 3.5 (Comsol Inc.) with MATLAB R2011a (The MathWorks, Inc.) for the boundary conditions mimicking typical experiments \cite{me,varnumsollStatic,fisherStatic}, (Fig.\ref{fig:geom}c, SI Section 3). 
cAMP concentration is varied on the left boundary $c(x{=}{-}w/2)$, zero on the right boundary $c(x{=}w/2) = 0$ and the normal component of cAMP flux is zero everywhere else, including the cell boundary \footnote{Zero-normal cAMP flux seems reasonable since the time scale for receptor internalization is 5 minutes [A. Serge et al. Integr. Biol., 3, 675-683, 2011] compared to the time scale of receptor dissociation of 1 second [M. Ueda et al. Science, 294, 864-867, 2001], so the binding and unbinding processes are in equilibrium.}. 
PDE concentration is zero on $p(x{=}\pm w/2) = 0$ while the normal flux is zero everywhere else except for the cell boundary where it's set to $P_0$.
The parameters used in simulations were: $K_M=10\,\mathrm{\mu M}$ \cite{KmcAMPPDEandPDI}, $D_{c}=444\,\mathrm{\mu m^{2}s^{-1}}$ \cite{DcAMP}, $D_{p}=70\,\mathrm{\mu m^{2}s^{-1}}$, $k_{2}=13,300\,\mathrm{s^{-1}}$(estimated; SI, Section 4), $r_c = 5\, \mathrm{\mu m}$. 

SNR results, as a function of PDE secretion flux $P_0$ and cAMP concentration on the left boundary $c(-w/2)$, for the relative gradient $r_c|\vec{\nabla} c|/c_0 = 1 \%$ are shown in Fig.\ref{fig:Results1}a. 
They show that PDE can substantially improve SNR for a range of $P_0$ and $c(-w/2)$ values and the improvement is better for large cAMP concentrations. If the midpoint concentration is $c_0 \lesssim K_d$ ($c(-w/2) \lesssim 2\, K_d$), then SNR cannot be increased further (Fig.\ref{fig:Results1}b). PDE can also broaden the range of cAMP detection by increasing the $c(-w/2)$ range for which $\mathrm{SNR} \geq 1$ (Fig.\ref{fig:Results1}c,d). This behavior is also reflected in the CI (Fig.\ref{fig:Results1}e,f). The SNR improvement by PDE also occurs when either the absolute gradient $|\vec{\nabla}c|$ or the midpoint concentration $c_0$ are fixed (SI, Section 5).

According to Fig.\ref{fig:Results1}, the relevant $P_0$ range between $10^{-12}$ and $10^{-10}\,\mathrm{mol\, m^{-2}s^{-1}}$, falls within the rough physiological range estimated here for PDE of $10^{-11}\,\mathrm{mol\, m^{-2}s^{-1}}$ (SI) and by others for Bar1 of $10^{-12}\,\mathrm{mol\, m^{-2}s^{-1}}$ (which degrades $\alpha$-factor pheromone signal in yeast) \cite{yeast2}.


%
%
% Fixed PDE concentration model
%
%
\emph{Fixed PDE concentration model.}--- Next, we consider the case of time-independent and spatially uniform PDE concentration, $p(x,t)=p_{0}$,  without a cell boundary in the middle, but otherwise same boundary conditions as before. We again vary cAMP concentration on the left boundary $c(-w/2)$ and set $c(w/2) = 0$. The solution of Eqs.\ref{eq:main_sys} is:
\begin{equation}
	c(x) = c(-w/2) \frac{\sinh\left(\frac{w}{2L}-\frac{x}{L}\right)}
		{\sinh\left(\frac{w}{L}\right)},\quad L=\sqrt{\frac{K_M D_c}{k_2p_0}}
	\label{eq:uniform_pde_analytic_sol}
\end{equation}
SNR is calculated by plugging this result into Eqs.\ref{eq:SNRdef},\ref{eq:RFB} and is shown in Fig.\ref{fig:uniform_pde_results}a,b.

