The analytical expression for SNR can be simplified under the approximation of shallow gradients $r_c|\vec{\nabla}c| \ll K_d$ which is well satisfied in this work ($\mathrm{max}(r_c|\vec{\nabla}c|/K_d) = 5\cdot10^{-3}$):

\begin{equation}
	\mathrm{SNR} \approx \frac{N K_d r_c |\vec{\nabla}c|}{2\sqrt{\sigma_B^2(c_0 + K_d)^2 + N c_0 K_d}}
\end{equation}
The similarity in SNR between Fig.\ref{fig:uniform_pde_results}a and Fig.\ref{fig:Results1}a (by rescaling the x axis) occurs because only the local PDE and cAMP concentrations near the cell are of importance.
 
At the midpoint $x = 0$, the cAMP concentration and gradient are (Fig.\ref{fig:uniform_pde_results}c):
\begin{equation}
	|\vec{\nabla} c| = \frac{c(-w/2)}{2L\sinh\left(\frac{w}{2L}\right)},\quad 
	c_0 = \frac{c(-w/2)}{2\cosh\left(\frac{w}{2L}\right)}
\end{equation}
which correctly reduce to their original values $|\vec{\nabla}c| = c(-w/2)/w$ and $c_0 = c(-w/2)/2$ in the the $p_0 \to 0$ ($L \to \infty$) limit. 

This shows that PDE acts by reducing the gradient but even more the average concentration, so the signal $\Delta R \propto |\vec{\nabla}c|/(c_0 + K_d)^2$ across the cell is enhanced. As before, Fig.\ref{fig:uniform_pde_results}d shows the signal $\Delta R$ can be improved only if the average (midpoint) concentration is $c_0 \gtrsim K_d$ without PDE. For PDE concentrations $\lesssim \,1\,\mathrm{nM}$, PDE can generate up to $\sim 1000$ receptors difference. 

One of the key contributors to enhanced SNR is the upper bound on the total noise (Fig.\ref{fig:uniform_pde_results}e), which is $\sqrt{\sigma_B^2 + N/(4I)} \approx 134$ at $c_0 = K_d$ (Eq.\ref{eq:signal_noise_def}). The fixed non-receptor noise $\sigma_B = 73$ sets a lower bound on the total noise. That means the overall scale of the noise is independent of PDE concentration. On the other hand, the signal does not have an upper bound, can be written as $\Delta R = N f(p_0)$. Then, $\mathrm{SNR} \propto f(p_0)$ enhancement completely comes from the increase in the signal $\Delta R$, through $f(p_0)$.
Under very high cAMP concentrations $c_0 \gtrsim 100\,K_d$, the PDE can enhance the signal (receptor occupancy difference) and also the SNR, by more than an order of magnitude (Fig.\ref{fig:uniform_pde_results}f), while the noise remains capped to its maximum, PDE-independent, value. 

Similar results are also reproduced numerically if we have the cell boundary in the middle of domain (SI, Section 6) like in fixed PDE secretion flux model and in full 3D space for the cAMP emitted by the point source (SI, Section 7).

%
% 	Discussion
%
\emph{Concluding remarks.}--- In summary, we investigated the effects of extracellular PDE on cAMP gradient sensing in \emph{D. discoideum}.
We find that the secretion of PDE by cells shifts their response towards higher cAMP concentrations (as expected) but can also greatly increase the SNR and broaden the range of signal detection. This contrasts an earlier conclusion reached using dimensional analysis \cite{mechanism1}. The SNR increase is directly related to the increase in the signal (differential receptor occupancy), since the noise is capped to the maximum value, independent of PDE. 

Previously, it has been experimentally observed that \emph{pdsA-} cells (which also lack membrane-bound PDE which is not considered here) respond to a lower range of cAMP concentrations \cite{pdsA1}, as predicted by our model. These predictions can be tested quantitatively by measuring CI across the range of cAMP concentrations for both wild-type and \emph{pdsA-} cells. 

Furthermore, the CI is observed to decrease if the cells are starved for longer time periods, and exposed to the same gradient $|\vec{\nabla} c| \approx 0.03 \,\mathrm{nM\,\mu m^{-1}}$, $c_0 \approx 30\,\mathrm{nM}$ (Fig.4 in \cite{fisherStatic}). This can also be explained by our model, since the peak of shifts towards higher cAMP concentrations if the PDE accumulates in the environment.

The effects discussed here also lead to different predictions between the experiments with static non-flowing gradients where cAMP gradients are affected by secreted PDE \cite{me,varnumsollStatic,fisherStatic}
and the experiments with static flowing gradients \cite{song,fuller-1,eberhard1} where the PDE is flushed away. The flow gradient experiments are considered advantageous since the cells are prevented to communicate with each other with cAMP (while not significantly distorting the local gradient around the cell \cite{ebFlow}), however they also completely wash away extracellular PDE (Section 8, SI). 

Finally, we neglected the effects of PDE inhibitor (PDI), which is expected to get secreted under high PDE levels \cite{PdePdiKd} and would effectively increase the Michaelis-Menten constant of the cAMP-PDE interaction towards millimolar range \cite{KmcAMPPDEandPDI}.


